1 Introduction

Insurance allows individuals and businesses to transfer financial risk to an insurer. When the covered event occurs, the insurer compensates the policyholder for the resulting losses. However, some events lead to claims that are so large that they pose a serious threat to the insurer’s financial stability, even risking insolvency.

To manage this, insurers rely on reinsurance: insurance for insurers. Reinsurers absorb part of the risk, helping insurers stay solvent and continue underwriting high-value policies. And yes, it goes even further. In some cases, reinsurers also buy insurance, known as retrocession. So, in a way, reinsurance is the financial version of “I know a guy who knows a guy who can help”.

Accurate modeling of large claims is crucial for understanding risk in insurance and reinsurance. The Pareto distribution is a natural candidate for this task due to its heavy-tailed nature. However, real-world reinsurance structures are rarely uniform. They often consist of multiple layers, each with its own retention and limit, designed to spread the impact of catastrophic events across several treaties. This layered approach ensures that even very rare, high-severity claims are adequately covered without concentrating risk in a single contract.

To reflect this layered reality, the piecewise Pareto model extends the classical Pareto by segmenting the tail into distinct intervals. Each segment can have its own parameters, allowing for a more flexible fit to observed data and a closer alignment with the structure of reinsurance programs. This approach provides a richer statistical framework for modeling extreme events while maintaining interpretability and consistency with actuarial principles. Beyond reinsurance, the piecewise Pareto has applications in areas such as operational risk, cyber insurance and any domain where extreme, layered risks need careful quantification.

In this article, we start by revisiting the Pareto Type I distribution and explore how the piecewise Pareto generalizes this concept to better represent complex, multi-layered risk structures. This article is educational in nature and is based on the following sources:

  • Embrechts, Klüppelberg, and Mikosch (2013);
  • Clark (1996);
  • Riegel (2018) .

2 The type I Pareto Distribution

2.1 Properties

2.1.1 Distribution functions

The Type I Pareto distribution is characterized by two key parameters, \(\alpha\) and a suitable large (loss) threshold \(t\). With \(X\) denoting a Pareto random variable, the survival function is given by

\[ S(x) = \Pr(X > x) = \left(\frac{t}{x}\right)^{\alpha}, \ \text{where} \quad x > t, \]

and the cumulative distribution function (CDF) by

\[ F(x) = 1 - \left(\frac{t}{x}\right)^{\alpha}. \] The corresponding probability density function is

\[ \begin{equation} \begin{aligned} f(x) &= \frac{d}{dx} F(x)\\ &= - t^\alpha \ \frac{d}{dx} \ x^{-\alpha}\\ &= t^{\alpha} \ \alpha \ x^{-\alpha - 1}\\ &= \frac{t^{\alpha} \ \alpha}{x^{\alpha + 1}}. \end{aligned} \end{equation} \]

The inverse CDF, or quantile function, can be derived as

\[ \begin{aligned} p &= 1 - \left(\frac{t}{x}\right)^{\alpha}\\ \mathcal{Q}(p) &= t (1 - p)^{-\frac{1}{\alpha}} \end{aligned} \] where \(p = F(x)\) and \(\mathcal{Q}(p) = F^{-1}(F(x))\). The Pareto distribution is useful to capture heavy-tailed phenomena where the probability of extreme values decays polynomially, controlled by the parameter \(\alpha\). A higher \(\alpha\) results in a thinner tail, meaning extreme values occur less frequently. This is illustrated in Figure 2.1, where we see that a larger \(\alpha\) results in a thinner tail, relative to a smaller \(\alpha\) value.

nSim = 1e5
Df = data.frame(
  x     = c(rPareto(nSim, 1e6, 2.5), rPareto(nSim, 1e6, 5)),
  Alpha = c(rep("\u03B1 = 2.5", nSim), rep("\u03B1 = 5", nSim))
)

As illustrated in the code above, we can use the functions from the Pareto package to generate random samples from a Pareto distribution. We can also do this by manually by employing inverse transform sampling, where we rely on the quantile function to generate random samples.

# Parameters
alpha = 5
t     = 1e6

# Inverse CDF (Quantile function)
Q <- Vectorize(function(p, alpha, t) t * (1 - p)^(-1 / alpha), vectorize.args = "p")

2.1.2 Moments

For \(\alpha > 1\), the expected value is equal to

\[ \begin{aligned} E[X] &= \int_t^\infty x f(x)\,dx \\ &= \alpha t^{\alpha} \int_t^\infty x^{-\alpha} dx\\ &= t \ \frac{\alpha}{\alpha - 1} \end{aligned} \]

and \(E[X] = \infty\) if \(\alpha \leq 1\). For a Pareto Type I with \(\alpha > 2\), the variance equals

\[ \mathrm{Var}(X) = \frac{\alpha t^2}{(\alpha-1)^2(\alpha-2)} \]

and \(\mathrm{Var}(X) = \infty\) if \(\alpha \in (1, 2]\).

Using the randomly generated sample, we can compare the empirical average with the theoretical average

c("Empirical average" = mean(x), "Theoretical average" = t * alpha / (alpha - 1))
##   Empirical average Theoretical average 
##             1250111             1250000

and compare the empirical variance to its theoretical counterpart.

c("Empirical variance" = var(x), "Theoretical variance" = t^2 * alpha / ((alpha - 1)^2 * (alpha - 2)))
##   Empirical variance Theoretical variance 
##         100914713011         104166666667

Comparing theoretical moments with their empirical counterparts serves as a practical validation step for both the model and its implementation. This exercise not only confirms that the model behaves as expected but also illustrates the influence of sampling variability. Particularly in heavy-tailed settings, where a few extreme observations can significantly distort sample estimates. Such comparisons highlight why large samples or robust estimation techniques are critical when dealing with fat-tailed distributions. In an insurance context, this process builds confidence that modeled losses are consistent with observed data and sufficiently stable to support pricing, capital allocation, and risk management decisions.

2.2 Mean excess

One of the key quantities associated with heavy-tailed distributions, such as the Pareto, is the mean excess function of \(x\) (Embrechts, Klüppelberg, and Mikosch 2013) \[ \begin{aligned} E[X - a | X > a] &= \frac{1}{S(a)} \int_a^\infty (x - a) f(x) dx \\ &= \frac{1}{S(a)} \int_a^\infty S(x) dx. \end{aligned} \] This quantity represents the expected excess over a threshold \(a\), given that the loss exceeds \(a\). For the Pareto Type I, this function has a particularly simple form for \(\alpha > 1\) \[ \begin{aligned} E[X - a | X > a] &= \frac{1}{\left(t / a \right)^{\alpha}} \int_a^\infty \left(\frac{t}{x}\right)^\alpha dx\\ &= \frac{a^\alpha}{t^\alpha} t^\alpha \left(\frac{a^{1 - \alpha}}{1 - \alpha}\right)\\ &= \frac{a}{\alpha - 1}. \end{aligned} \]

We can verify this empirically as follows

a = 1.25e6
c("Empirical mean excess" = mean((x - a)[x > a]), "Theoretical Mean Excess" = a / (alpha - 1))
##   Empirical mean excess Theoretical Mean Excess 
##                312344.4                312500.0

This property illustrates the “lack of memory” in the tail. As the threshold \(a\) increases, the expected excess grows linearly with \(a\). Closely related to the mean excess is the unconditional expectation of the excess above \(a\), defined as

\[ \mathbb{E}[(X - a)_+] = \int_a^\infty (x - a) f(x) \, dx, \]

where \((X - a)_+ = \max(X - a, 0)\). This quantity represents the expected overshoot without conditioning on \(X > a\) and is useful when modeling aggregate excess amounts. Both the conditional and unconditional forms play an important role in understanding tail behavior and in applications such as risk modeling.

The mean excess function describes the expected overshoot for a single observation. To extend this to an aggregate measure, we incorporate the frequency. Assuming independence between the frequency \(N\) and severity \(X\), the expected aggregate excess above \(a\) is \[ E[L] = E[N] \ E[(X - a)_+]. \] However, in some cases we only have information about the expected frequency in excess of \(a\), which is calculated as \(E[N | X > a] = E[N] S_X(a)\). Using this conditional frequency, we calculate the aggregate excess as \[ E[L] = E[N | X > a] \ E[X - a \mid X > a]. \]

One of the key challenges in modeling extreme events is that very large, infrequent observations can dominate the aggregate outcome. One way to address this is by introducing a cap that restricts the impact of observations exceeding the retention point \(a\), up to a limit \(l\). Mathematically, this is represented as \[ \min\{l, (X - a)_+\}. \] This structure is widely used in a variety of applications as it reduces sensitivity to extreme outliers while still capturing tail behavior. For example, in insurance and finance, layered structures help manage exposure to catastrophic losses. Similarly, in cloud computing or IT services, tiered pricing models apply a cap on usage charges beyond a certain threshold, ensuring that a single unusually high usage event does not dominate overall costs. To analyze such layers, we use an adjusted version of the mean excess function that accounts for the cap

\[ \begin{aligned} E[\min\{l, (X - a)_+\} \mid X > a] &= \frac{1}{S(a)} \left[ \int_a^{a + l} (x - a) f(x) \ dx + \int_{a+l}^{\infty} l \cdot f(x) dx \right] \\ &= \frac{1}{S(a)} \left[ \int_a^{a + l} (x - a) f(x) \, dx + l \cdot S(a + l) \right]. \end{aligned} \]

In practice, it is often convenient to align the retention \(a\) with the threshold \(t\) used to define large values. Under this assumption, the layer only applies to values already considered “above the threshold”. For the remainder of this document, we assume \(a = t\).

For distributions such as the Pareto Type I, where \(t\) is the lower bound of the support, setting \(a = t\) has an additional implication. Conditioning on \(X > t\) does not change the expectation, so the conditional and unconditional mean excess functions coincide. For a Pareto Type I, the adjusted mean excess function takes on the following form (see 5.1 for the proof)

\[ E[\min\{l, (X - t)+\}] = \frac{1}{\alpha - 1} \left( t - t^\alpha (t + l)^{1 - \alpha} \right). \] As before, we use simulated data to verify whether our implementation behaves as expected. Specifically, we compare the empirical mean excess with the theoretical result. If we have a layer with a limit \(l\) of 1 million in excess \(t\) of 1 million, we obtain the following result

t = 1e6
l = 1e6
c("Empirical Mean Excess" = mean(pmin(pmax(x - t, 0), l)),
  "Theoretical Mean Excess" = 1 / (alpha - 1) * (t - t^alpha * (t + l)^(1 - alpha)))
##   Empirical Mean Excess Theoretical Mean Excess 
##                  234609                  234375

2.3 Upper truncation

Hence, in some applications, it is useful to impose an upper bound \(T > t\) on the distribution, representing a maximum possible value or cap. This leads to a truncated distribution, where the original density is rescaled to ensure it integrates to 1 over the interval \([t, T]\). Truncation is important when modeling capped exposures or maximum possible values. It ensures that the model reflects realistic upper bounds and truncation also serves as a foundation for piecewise Pareto models.

For a Pareto Type I distribution, the truncated density becomes

\[ \begin{aligned} f_{Tr}(x) &= \frac{f(x)}{F(T)}\\ &= \frac{t^{\alpha} \ \alpha x^{-\alpha - 1}}{1 - \left( t / T \right)^\alpha}. \end{aligned} \]

Here, \(F(T)\) equals the CDF value at the upper truncation point \(T\). We apply this scaling factor to ensure that the truncated distribution is a proper probability distribution. That is, \[ \int_t^T f_{Tr}(x) dx = 1. \]

You can check this using numerical approximation or, if you want to have some fun, try working out the analytical proof yourself. The numerical result below confirms that we have a valid probability distribution, as the total area under the curve equals 1.

t     = 1e6
limit = 2.5e6
alpha = 1.26
Fx   <- function(x, t, alpha) 1 - (t / x)^alpha
fxTr <- function(x, t, alpha, limit) t^alpha * alpha * x^(-alpha - 1) / Fx(limit, t, alpha)
print(integrate(fxTr, t, limit, alpha = alpha, t = t, limit = limit))
## 1 with absolute error < 6.6e-14

The expected value of the truncated Pareto type I is given by (see 5.3 for the proof)

\[ \begin{aligned} E[X_{Tr}] &= \frac{t^\alpha}{F(T)} \frac{\alpha}{1 - \alpha} \left( T^{1 - \alpha} - t^{1 - \alpha} \right).\\ \end{aligned} \]

For our example, this equals

t^alpha / Fx(limit, t, alpha) * alpha / (1 - alpha) * (limit^(-alpha + 1) - t^(-alpha + 1))
## [1] 1500164

To generate a random sample from a truncated Pareto distribution, we rely on the quantile function (see 5.2) \[\begin{align*} \mathcal{Q}(p) = t \left(1 - p F(T) \right)^{-1 / \alpha}. \tag{2.1} \end{align*}\]

Below is an example of how we would implement it in R. Comparing the empirical with the theoretical average, we note that the deviation is low in this example.

# Inverse CDF (Quantile function)
Q <- Vectorize(function(p, alpha, t, limit) t * (1 - p * Fx(limit, t, alpha))^(-1 / alpha), vectorize.args = "p")

# Example: generate random values using inverse transform sampling
set.seed(1)
nSample = 1e5
u       = runif(nSample)
x       = Q(u, alpha = alpha, t = t, limit = limit)
mean(x)
## [1] 1500207

3 The Piecewise Pareto Distribution

3.1 Why piecewise?

Real‑world data with heavy tails, such as city population size, or file sizes in computer networks, rarely follows a single Pareto distribution. While the Pareto distribution is a powerful model for extremes, its simplicity can become a limitation when applied to complex data sets. Different parts of the distribution often reflect different underlying mechanisms, making a single distribution inadequate.

The same principle applies in insurance. Consider a portfolio of claims:

  • Small, frequent claims (e.g., minor property damage) dominate the lower range and tend to have a relatively light tail;
  • Large claims (e.g., severe bodily injury) are rarer and exhibit a heavier tail, reflecting greater variability;
  • Catastrophic events (e.g., natural disasters) are extremely rare but potentially enormous, and their tail behavior changes again due to physical and contractual limits.

A piecewise Pareto distribution addresses this by dividing the range into segments, each with its own Pareto parameter. This approach provides flexibility to capture the nuances of empirical data while preserving the interpretability of Pareto‑based modeling. It is particularly useful when modeling layered phenomena, where different mechanisms dominate at different scales.

3.2 Properties

The piecewise Pareto distribution is an example of a spliced distribution, where different segments follow different distributions (Riegel 2018). In this case, it extends the classical Pareto distribution by introducing a set of breakpoints \(t_1 < t_2 < \dots < t_n\), dividing the range into multiple intervals. Each interval \([t_i, t_{i + 1}]\) follows a separate Pareto distribution with its own \(\alpha_i\) parameter.

3.2.1 Distribution functions

To define a piecewise Pareto distribution, the survival function must remain continuous across breakpoints. For a segment starting at \(t_k\), the survival function takes the form

\[ S(x) = S(t_k) \left( \frac{t_k}{x} \right)^{\alpha_k}, \quad t_k \leq x < t_{k + 1}, \]

where \(S(t_k)\) represents the survival probability at the start of the segment. These values are computed recursively to ensure continuity

\[ S(t_k) = \begin{cases} 1, & k = 1, \\ S(t_{k - 1}) \left( \dfrac{t_{k - 1}}{t_k} \right)^{\alpha_{k - 1}}, & 2 \leq k \leq n. \end{cases} \]

This approach ensures that the probability of exceeding \(x\) is correctly proportioned within its segment, preventing discontinuities or misallocated probability mass. Expanding this recursively from the first breakpoint, we obtain the full survival function

\[ S(x) = \left[ \prod_{i=1}^{k-1} \left(\frac{t_i}{t_{i+1}}\right)^{\alpha_i} \right] \left(\frac{t_k}{x}\right)^{\alpha_k}, \quad t_k \leq x < t_{k+1}. \] The example below demonstrates the piecewise Pareto distribution in practice, using the following specifications:

  • thresholds (attachments) \(\mathbf{t} = (1 000 000, 2 500 000, 5 000 000)\);
  • layer-specific alphas \(\mathbf{\alpha} = (1.25, 1.75, 2)\).
# Breakpoints and alphas
t      = c(1e6, 2.5e6, 5e6)
alphas = c(1.25, 1.75, 2)

# Function to compute survival at t_k
S_tk <- function(k, t, alphas) {
  if (k == 1)
    return(1)
  else
    prod((t[1:(k - 1)] / t[2:k])^alphas[1:(k - 1)])
}

# Function to compute survival at x
SxPwP <- function(x, t, alpha) {
  k = findInterval(x, t, rightmost.closed = TRUE)
  if (k == 0)
    return(1)
  else if (k > length(alpha))
    return(0)
  else
    S_tk(k, t, alpha) * (t[k] / x)^alpha[k]
}

# Survival probability at t_2 = 2 500 000
S_tk(2, t, alphas)
## [1] 0.3181083
# Sanity check
1 - pPiecewisePareto(t[2], t, alphas)
## [1] 0.3181083
# Survival probability at x = 1 500 000
SxPwP(1.5e6, t, alphas)
## [1] 0.6024013
# Sanity check
1 - pPiecewisePareto(1.5e6, t, alphas)
## [1] 0.6024013

The CDF of a piecewise Pareto is defined as

\[ \begin{aligned} F(x) &= 1 - \left(\frac{t_k}{x}\right)^{\alpha_k} \prod_{i=1}^{k-1} \left(\frac{t_i}{t_{i+1}}\right)^{\alpha_i}\\ &= 1 - \left(\frac{t_k}{x}\right)^{\alpha_k} S(t_k) \end{aligned} \]

and the inverse CDF as

\[ \begin{aligned} p^{*} &= 1 - \left(\frac{t_{k}}{x}\right)^{\alpha_{k}} S\left(t_{k}\right) \\ \left(\frac{t_{k}}{x}\right)^{\alpha_{k}} & = S\left(t_{k}\right)^{-1}\left[1 - p^{*}\right] \\ \mathcal{Q}(p^*) &= t_{k}\left(S\left(t_{k}\right)^{-1}\left(1 - p^{*}\right)\right)^{-\frac{1}{\alpha_{k}}} \end{aligned} \] where \(p^{*} = F(x)\) and \(\mathcal{Q}(p^*) = F^{-1}(F(x))\). This illustrates that \(S(t_k)\) acts as a scaling factor, ensuring that the probability within each segment is properly normalized. Notice that this expression closely resembles equation (2.1) for the truncated Pareto I. In fact, each segment \([t_k, t_{k + 1}]\) can be interpreted as a truncated single Pareto distribution (see 5.4).

# CDF
FxPwP <- function(x, t, alpha) 1 - SxPwP(x, t, alpha)

# Inverse CDF (Quantile function)
QxPwP <- function(p, t, alpha) {
  findK <- function(p, k, t, alpha) {
    if(k > length(alpha))
      stop("Something went wrong")
    if(k == length(alpha))
      return(k)
    S_lower = S_tk(k, t, alpha)
    S_upper = S_tk(k + 1, t, alpha)
    if(p >= 1 - S_lower && p < 1 - S_upper)
      return(k)
    else
      findK(p, k + 1, t, alpha)
      
  }
  k       = findK(p, 1, t, alpha)
  S_lower = S_tk(k, t, alpha)
  t[k] * (1 / S_lower * (1 - p))^(-1 / alpha[k])
}

# Example: Quantile at p = c(0.25, 0.75, 0.95)
Qx <- Vectorize(function(p, t, alpha) QxPwP(p, t, alpha), vectorize.args = "p")
Qx(c(0.25, 0.75, 0.95), t, alphas)
## [1] 1258783 2869006 6876560
# Sanity check
qPiecewisePareto(c(0.25, 0.75, 0.95), t, alphas)
## [1] 1258783 2869006 6876560

Figure 3.1 shows simulated claims from a piecewise Pareto distribution. Each color represents a different segment of the distribution, separated by the dashed vertical lines (the attachment points). Within each segment, the tail index \(\alpha_k\) determines how quickly the probability of large claims decreases. Lower \(\alpha_k\) values correspond to heavier tails, meaning large claims are more likely in that range.

The histogram and smoothed density curves illustrate the relative frequency of claims within each segment. Notice how the slope and spread change across segments. This reflects the flexibility of the piecewise Pareto model to capture different tail behaviors in different ranges, rather than assuming a single decay rate for the entire tail.

x = Qx(runif(1e5), t, alphas)
K = length(alphas)

                        ")")

3.3 Mean excess

Building on the concepts from the single Pareto case, we now consider the mean excess function for the piecewise Pareto. The pdf of a single piece is equal to \[ \begin{aligned} f_k(x) &= \frac{d}{dx} F_k(x)\\ &= - S(t_k) \ t_k^{\alpha_k} \ \frac{d}{dx} \ x^{-\alpha_{k}}\\ &= S(t_k) \ t_k^{\alpha_k} \ \alpha_{k} \ x^{-\alpha_k - 1} \end{aligned} \] Hence, the mean excess for layer \(k\), with attachment \(t_k\) and limit \(l_k\), is given by \[ \begin{aligned} E[\min\{l_k, (X - t_k)_+\}] &= \int_{t_k}^{t_k + l_k} (x - t_k) f_k(x) dx + \int_{t_k+l_k}^{\infty} l_k \cdot f_k(x) dx \\ &= S(t_k) \left( \int_t^{t_k+l_k} (x - t_k) t_k^{\alpha_k} \alpha_{k} x^{-\alpha_k - 1} dx + \int_{t_k+l_k}^{\infty} l_k \cdot t_k^{\alpha_k} \alpha_{k} x^{-\alpha_k - 1} dx \right)\\ &= S(t_k) \left( \frac{1}{\alpha_k - 1} (t_k - t_k^{\alpha_k} (t_k + l_k)^{1 - \alpha_k}) \right). \end{aligned} \] and the conditional mean excess by \[ \begin{aligned} E[\min\{l_k, (X - t_k)_+\} | X > t_k] = \frac{1}{\alpha_k - 1} (t_k - t_k^{\alpha_k} (t_k + l_k)^{1 - \alpha_k}). \end{aligned} \]

Consequently, we see that the mean excess of a specific layer in the piecewise Pareto is determined by the layer specific \(\alpha_k\) parameter, given the layer’s attachment and limit.

To validate the theoretical expression, we compare it against an empirical estimate. As before, we simulate data with the following specifications:

  • thresholds \(\mathbf{t} = (1 000 000, 2 500 000, 5 000 000)\);
  • limits \(\mathbf{l} = (1 500 000, 2 500 000, 100 000 000)\);
  • layer-specific alphas \(\mathbf{\alpha} = (1.25, 1.75, 2)\).

For each segment, we calculate the observed mean excess within the layer and compare it with the analytical formula.

t      = c(1e6, 2.5e6, 5e6)
alphas = c(1.25, 1.75, 2)
l      = c(diff(t), 1e8)
x      = Qx(runif(1e4), t, alphas)

for(k in seq_along(alphas)) {
  res = 
    c(

        ((t[k] + l[k])^(1 - alphas[k]) - t[k]^(1 - alphas[k]))
    )
  cat(paste0("Layer ", k, ":\n\n"))
  print(res)
  ## Sanity check
  cat("\n\nSanity check:\n")
  print(PiecewisePareto_Layer_Mean(l[k], t[k], t, alphas))
  cat("\n\n")
}

To calculate the aggregate expected loss, we require the expected number of claims per layer. Earlier, we introduced the concept of conditional frequency in excess of a threshold, expressed as

\[ E[N \mid X > a] = E[N] \cdot S_X(a). \]

This formulation allows us to estimate the expected number of claims above a retention level \(a\), based on the overall frequency and the tail probability. In the piecewise Pareto framework, we build on this idea by modeling the frequency decay across thresholds. The following relationship between frequencies and thresholds holds

\[ \alpha_i = \frac{\log \left(f_{i+1} / f_i\right)}{\log \left(t_i / t_{i+1}\right)}. \]

Rearranging gives

\[ \frac{f_{i+1}}{f_i} = \left(\frac{t_i}{t_{i+1}}\right)^{\alpha_i}. \]

This implies that the frequency above a higher threshold can be derived from the previous one. Using this result, we can rewrite the cumulative distribution function (CDF)

\[ F(x) = 1 - \left(\frac{t_{k}}{x}\right)^{\alpha_{k}} \prod_{i=1}^{k-1}\left(\frac{t_{i}}{t_{i+1}}\right)^{\alpha_{i}}, \]

as

\[ F(x) = 1 - \left(\frac{t_k}{x}\right)^{\alpha_k} \cdot \frac{f_k}{f_1}. \]

From this, it follows that at each breakpoint \(t_k\), the frequency satisfies

\[ F(t_{k}) = 1 - \frac{f_{k}}{f_{1}}, \quad \text{so that} \quad f_{k} = f_{1}(1 - F(t_{k})). \]

In practice, this means that, once you know the base frequency \(f_1\) and the tail indices \(\alpha_i\), you can compute the expected number of claims above any threshold.

# Example frequencies at t1
f1 <- 20

# Compute frequency at other thresholds
(fVec = f1 * sapply(t, function(x) SxPwP(x, t, alphas)))
## [1] 20.000000  6.362166  1.891483

This approach allows us to propagate the frequency across layers in a consistent and interpretable way. With the frequency \(f_k\) at each layer determined, we can then compute the expected loss for layer \(k\) using \[ \begin{aligned} E[L_k] = f_k \cdot E[\min\{l_k, (X - t_k)_+\} | X > t_k]. \end{aligned} \]

3.4 Illustration

Let’s bring everything together in a small example. We assume that the number of claims \(N\) follows a Poisson distribution and that \(E[N | X > t_1] = 20\). For the piecewise Pareto, we use the same parameter settings as before:

  • thresholds \(\mathbf{t} = (1 000 000, 2 500 000, 5 000 000)\);
  • limits \(\mathbf{l} = (1 500 000, 2 500 000, 100 000 000)\);
  • layer-specific alphas \(\mathbf{\alpha} = (1.25, 1.75, 2)\).

The \(\text{VaR}\) is the (negative) amount \(\text{VaR}_\alpha\) (Olivieri and Pitacco 2015) such that \[ P(Z \leq \text{VaR}_\alpha) = \alpha \] and the \(\text{TVaR}\) is the (negative) amount defined as \[ \begin{aligned} \text{TVaR}_\alpha &= E[Z | Z < \text{VaR}_\alpha]\\ &= \frac{\int_{-\infty}^ {\text{VaR}_\alpha} z \ f(z) \ dz}{P(Z < \text{VaR}_\alpha)}. \end{aligned} \] Here \(Z\) denotes the random variable capturing the monetary result, where a negative value represents a loss and a positive value profit. If we take \(\alpha\)-values 0.05, 0.01, 0.005 and 0.001 and compute both the \(\text{VaR}\) and \(\text{TVaR}\) for our simulated data, we obtain the following results depicted in Table 3.2.

ES <- function(x, p) {
  xS = sort(x)
  k  = floor(p * length(x))
  mean(xS[1:k])
}


a    = c(0.05, 0.01, 0.005, 0.001)
VaR  = as.numeric(quantile(PL, a))
TVaR = sapply(a, function(a) ES(PL, a))

res = data.frame(
  `Confidence level` = sprintf("%.1f%%", (1 - a) * 1e2),

4 Conclusion

The piecewise Pareto model extends the classical Pareto by introducing local tail indices, allowing for different tail behaviors across segments. This makes it particularly suited for layered structures such as reinsurance programs, where attachment points and limits are fixed but tail behavior varies across ranges. Beyond reinsurance, the same principles apply to other domains with extreme, layered risks, such as operational or cyber risk.

In this blog post, I provide an overview of the theory and demonstrate how the model can be applied in practice. We explore how to compute expected losses, how to simulate data, and examine the aggregate loss distribution to highlight the importance of tail risk measures such as Value-at-Risk and Tail Value-at-Risk. These insights are essential for decision-making in risk management, capital allocation, and stress testing.

Ultimately, the piecewise Pareto offers a balance between flexibility and tractability. It captures real-world complexity without sacrificing interpretability. Whether used for pricing, capital modeling, or scenario analysis, it remains a powerful tool for modeling heavy-tailed phenomena in diverse applications.

5 Appendix

5.1 Mean Excess Pareto Type I

For a Pareto, the mean excess for a layer with limit \(l\) in excess of \(t\) is given by \[ \begin{aligned} \mathbb{E}[\min((X - t)_+, l)] &= \int_t^{t+l} (x - t) f(x) dx + \int_{t+l}^{\infty} l \cdot f(x) dx\\ \end{aligned} \] where \(f(x) = \alpha t^\alpha x^{-\alpha - 1}\). We use \(I_1 = \int_t^{t+l} (x - t) f(x) dx\) and \(I_2 = \int_{t+l}^{\infty} l \cdot f(x) dx\). We start by deriving

\[ \begin{aligned} I_1 &= \int_t^{t+l} (x - t) \cdot \alpha t^\alpha x^{-\alpha - 1} dx\\ &= \alpha t^\alpha \int_t^{t+l} (x - t) x^{-\alpha - 1} dx \end{aligned} \] We define \(u = x - t \rightarrow x = t + u\), \(dx = du\) and then the limits become \(u \in [0, l]\). \[ I_1 = \alpha t^\alpha \int_0^l u (t + u)^{-\alpha - 1} du \]

Using integration by parts \[ \begin{aligned} \int_0^l u (t + u)^{-\alpha - 1} du &= -\frac{l (t + l)^{-\alpha}}{\alpha} + \frac{1}{\alpha} \int_0^l (t + u)^{-\alpha} du \\ &= -\frac{l (t + l)^{-\alpha}}{\alpha} + \frac{1}{\alpha} \cdot \frac{(t + l)^{1 - \alpha} - t^{1 - \alpha}}{1 - \alpha}. \end{aligned} \] Hence, \[ I_1 = t^\alpha \left[-l (t + l)^{-\alpha} + \frac{(t + l)^{1 - \alpha} - t^{1 - \alpha}}{1 - \alpha} \right] \]

The second integral is equal to \[ \begin{aligned} I_2 &= l \cdot \int_{t + l}^\infty \alpha t^\alpha x^{-\alpha - 1} dx \\ &= l \cdot \alpha t^\alpha \cdot \frac{1}{\alpha} (t + l)^{-\alpha} = l t^\alpha (t + l)^{-\alpha} \end{aligned} \]

and adding \(I_1 + I_2\), we obtain \[ \begin{aligned} \mathbb{E}[\min((X - t)_+, l)] &= t^\alpha \left[-l (t + l)^{-\alpha} + \frac{(t + l)^{1 - \alpha} - t^{1 - \alpha}}{1 - \alpha} \right] + l t^\alpha (t + l)^{-\alpha} \\ &= t^\alpha \cdot \frac{(t + l)^{1 - \alpha} - t^{1 - \alpha}}{1 - \alpha}\\ &= \boxed{\frac{1}{\alpha - 1} \left( t - t^\alpha (t + l)^{1 - \alpha} \right)} \end{aligned} \]

5.2 Quantile function of the truncated Pareto

\[ \begin{aligned} p &= \frac{1}{F(T)} \left(1 - \left(\frac{t}{x}\right)^\alpha \right)\\ \left(\frac{t}{x}\right)^\alpha &= (1 - p F(T))\\ x &= t \left(1 - p F(T) \right)^{-1 / \alpha} \end{aligned} \]

5.3 Expected value of the truncated Pareto

For a truncated Pareto Type I, the expected value equals \[ \begin{aligned} E[X_{Tr}] &= \int_t^T x f_{Tr}(x) dx\\ &= \frac{t^\alpha \alpha}{F(T)} \int_t^T x^{-\alpha} dx\\ &= \frac{t^\alpha}{F(T)} \frac{\alpha}{1 - \alpha} \left( T^{1 - \alpha} - t^{1 - \alpha} \right).\\ \end{aligned} \] In R, we can perform some sanity checks of this result by using a simple example. Let us take the parameters as defined below in the code.

t     = 1e6
limit = 2.5e6
alpha = 1.26

Using the analytical formula for the expected value, we get

t^alpha / Fx(limit, t, alpha) * alpha / (1 - alpha) * (limit^(-alpha + 1) - t^(-alpha + 1))
## [1] 1500164

and as sanity check, we perform numerical integration and check if we obtain the same result.

ExTr <- function(x, t, alpha, limit) x * t^alpha * alpha * x^(-alpha - 1) / Fx(limit, t, alpha)
print(integrate(ExTr, t, limit, alpha = alpha, t = t, limit = limit))
## 1500164 with absolute error < 1.7e-08

and luckily, our sanity check passes.

5.4 Equivalence between the truncated Pareto and a piecewise Pareto segment

Let a piecewise Pareto have segment \(k\) supported on \([t_k, t_{k+1}]\) with shape \(\alpha_k>0\), and let \[ S(x) = \Pr(X>x), \qquad F(x) = 1 - S(x). \] Assume the usual Pareto form within the segment: \[ S(x) \;=\; S(t_k)\left(\frac{t_k}{x}\right)^{\alpha_k}, \quad t_k \le x \le t_{k+1}, \qquad\text{so that}\qquad S(t_{k+1}) = S(t_k)\left(\frac{t_k}{t_{k+1}}\right)^{\alpha_k}. \]

Define the unconditional CDF on the segment by \[ F(x) \;=\; 1 - S(t_k)\left(\frac{t_k}{x}\right)^{\alpha_k}, \qquad t_k \le x \le t_{k+1}, \] and the conditional (within-segment) probability level by \[ p_{\mathrm{cond}} \;=\; \frac{F(x)-F(t_k)}{F(t_{k+1})-F(t_k)} \;=\; \frac{p^{*} - F(t_k)}{F(t_{k+1}) - F(t_k)}, \] where \(p^{*}=F(x)\) is the (unconditional) CDF value at \(x\).

Then the quantile written in terms of the unconditional level \(p^{*}\) is equal to the quantile written in terms of the conditional level \(p_{\mathrm{cond}}\), and both coincide with the quantile of a Pareto\((t_k,\alpha_k)\) truncated above at \(t_{k+1}\): \[ \boxed{ \; \mathcal{Q}(p^{*}) \;=\; t_k \left(\frac{1-p^{*}}{S(t_k)}\right)^{-1/\alpha_k} \;=\; t_k \Big(1 - p_{\mathrm{cond}}\big(1 - (t_k/t_{k+1})^{\alpha_k}\big)\Big)^{-1/\alpha_k} \;=\; \mathcal{Q}_k(p_{\mathrm{cond}}). \; } \]

  1. Upper-truncated Pareto on \([t_k,t_{k+1}]\).
    The conditional (truncated) CDF is \[ F_{\mathrm{trunc}}(x) \;=\; \frac{F(x)-F(t_k)}{F(t_{k+1})-F(t_k)} \;=\; \frac{1-(t_k/x)^{\alpha_k}}{1-(t_k/t_{k+1})^{\alpha_k}}, \qquad t_k \le x \le t_{k+1}. \] Setting \(p_{\mathrm{cond}}=F_{\mathrm{trunc}}(x)\) and solving for \(x\) gives the (truncated) quantile \[ \mathcal{Q}_k(p_{\mathrm{cond}}) \;=\; t_k \Big(1 - p_{\mathrm{cond}}\big(1 - (t_k/t_{k+1})^{\alpha_k}\big)\Big)^{-1/\alpha_k}. \tag{1} \]

  2. Piecewise Pareto (unconditional) on segment \(k\).
    The unconditional CDF on the segment is \[ F(x) \;=\; 1 - S(t_k)\left(\frac{t_k}{x}\right)^{\alpha_k}, \] so for an unconditional level \(p^{*}=F(x)\), \[ \left(\frac{t_k}{x}\right)^{\alpha_k} \;=\; \frac{1-p^{*}}{S(t_k)}, \quad\Rightarrow\quad \mathcal{Q}(p^{*}) \;=\; t_k \left(\frac{1-p^{*}}{S(t_k)}\right)^{-1/\alpha_k}. \tag{2} \]

  3. Relating unconditional and conditional probabilities within the segment.
    At the boundaries, \[ F(t_k) = 1 - S(t_k),\qquad F(t_{k+1}) = 1 - S(t_{k+1}) = 1 - S(t_k)\left(\frac{t_k}{t_{k+1}}\right)^{\alpha_k}. \] Hence \[ F(t_{k+1}) - F(t_k) \;=\; S(t_k) - S(t_{k+1}) \;=\; S(t_k)\Big(1 - (t_k/t_{k+1})^{\alpha_k}\Big). \] By definition, \[ p_{\mathrm{cond}} \;=\; \frac{p^{*}-F(t_k)}{F(t_{k+1})-F(t_k)} \;=\; \frac{p^{*} - (1 - S(t_k))}{S(t_k)\big(1 - (t_k/t_{k+1})^{\alpha_k}\big)}. \] Solving for \(1-p^{*}\) yields \[ 1 - p^{*} \;=\; S(t_k)\Big(1 - p_{\mathrm{cond}}\big(1 - (t_k/t_{k+1})^{\alpha_k}\big)\Big). \tag{3} \]

  4. Equivalence of quantiles.
    Substitute (3) into the unconditional quantile (2): \[ \mathcal{Q}(p^{*}) \;=\; t_k \left( \frac{S(t_k)\big(1 - p_{\mathrm{cond}}(1 - (t_k/t_{k+1})^{\alpha_k})\big)}{S(t_k)} \right)^{-1/\alpha_k} \;=\; t_k \Big(1 - p_{\mathrm{cond}}(1 - (t_k/t_{k+1})^{\alpha_k})\Big)^{-1/\alpha_k}. \] This coincides exactly with the truncated quantile (1). Therefore \[ \boxed{ \mathcal{Q}(p^{*}) \;=\; \mathcal{Q}_k(p_{\mathrm{cond}}), } \] i.e., the unconditional piecewise Pareto quantile on segment \(k\) equals the upper-truncated Pareto quantile once the probability is conditioned to the segment.

Remarks. When \(t_{k+1}=\infty\), the segment is untruncated and the conditional expression reduces to the usual Pareto quantile \(t_k (1-p_{\mathrm{cond}})^{-1/\alpha_k}\).
